the best parts of the executive presence and influence program
    were the videos and the content. useem and massey did a great job in the videos
    and kept me engaged, interested and wanting to learn more. i also appreciate that
    the content allowed me an opportunity to expand my thinking beyond what i already
    know and has given me a different view of my organization and how i can improve
    in my role as director of communications.;
column6:
i really did not like or appreciate the discussion boards. there are
    just too many people taking the program and i do not have time to read the posts
    or respond thoughtfully to each one.; i have taken online courses like this
    before, but there were only 9-12 people in the program-- and it makes for a more
    manageable discussion board. as a solution, i recommend breaking the participants
    up into groups of ten for team discussions vs. total participant discussions.
    not only will you have engaging discussions, but you would be encouraging network
    within the smaller groups.;

    celebrated in society. empowering, inclusivity, open-mindedness, collaboration,
    meritocracy—who can ever say any of these are bad ideas? but at work, we face
    the reality that may contradict these high ideals. so, how do you act? keep being
    blind to reality? join the dark side? this course showed me the other way and
    taught me to accept reality and act ethically to influence and lead to desired
    change.;

column5:
the best parts of the executive presence and influence program
    were the videos and the content. useem and massey did a great job in the videos
    and kept me engaged, interested and wanting to learn more. i also appreciate that
    the content allowed me an opportunity to expand my thinking beyond what i already
    know and has given me a different view of my organization and how i can improve
    in my role as director of communications.;
column6:
i really did not like or appreciate the discussion boards. there are
    just too many people taking the program and i do not have time to read the posts
    or respond thoughtfully to each one.; i have taken online courses like this
    before, but there were only 9-12 people in the program-- and it makes for a more
    manageable discussion board. as a solution, i recommend breaking the participants
    up into groups of ten for team discussions vs. total participant discussions.
    not only will you have engaging discussions, but you would be encouraging network
    within the smaller groups.;
